title.narrative: NUTRITION SERVICES AND CARE

description.narrative: National, provincial and district health authorities have improved capacity and the necessary supplies to ensure the delivery of nutrition-specific interventions to prevent excess morbidity and mortality among boys, girls and women, including during emergencies., which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Cross-Sectoral - Monitoring, Data And Situation Analyses, Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Supply And Logistics, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Emergency Programme Implementation

description.narrative: Throughout 2021,;173 children under five years of age;have been admitted and treated for Severe Acute Malnutrition (SAM) against a yearly target of 2,000. Among these, only;36% (63);of them have been cured, meeting the global threshold for cure rates. A total of;3,903 school-aged children;have been provided nutrition services in the;three pilot provinces of NCD, WHP and Western Province. Micronutrient powder supplements were received by 7,760 children aged 6-59 months, 5,569 of the same age group received vitamin A supplementation. About 9,105 pregnant and lactating women received counselling on appropriate nutrition for adolescent, maternal and infant and young children. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:29/12/2021
